# API Integration Protocol

Before writing integration code, **always read the relevant API docs and source conventions first**. This prevents reinventing filtering, using wrong storage backends, or missing existing capabilities.

## Required Checks

### 1. Spaces API (`spaces-api.js`)
- `items.list(spaceId, opts)` supports: `type`, `pinned`, `tags`, `anyTags`, `limit`, `offset`, `includeContent`
- `items.get(spaceId, itemId)` returns full item with content
- Tags are the canonical way to filter by asset origin (e.g. WISER Playbooks tags items `riff-source`)
- **Never use `clipboard:get-item-content` for Spaces items** -- different storage system, IDs don't match

### 2. IPC Registry (`lib/ipc-registry.js`)
- Single source of truth for all IPC channel names
- Check before creating new IPC handlers -- one may already exist

### 3. Preload Bridges (`preload.js`, `preload-spaces.js`)
- Check what's already exposed to renderer via `contextBridge`
- Key namespaces: `window.spaces`, `window.clipboard`, `window.api`, `window.ai`, `window.playbook`, `window.devTools`

### 4. Module Manager (`module-manager.js`)
- Web tools are registered dynamically and listed via `module:get-web-tools`
- Open tools via `module:open-web-tool` with optional `{ url }` override for deep links
- **Never hardcode web tool URLs** -- look up by name from the registry

### 5. External App Conventions
When integrating with features built by external apps (WISER Playbooks, Ticketing, etc.):
- **Fetch and read the app's source** to understand how it stores/tags/identifies its data
- Check what tags, metadata fields, or content markers it uses
- Use those same signals for filtering -- don't invent heuristics

